### Quiz 4 answers

1. Healthy.
2. Not converged (drift means non-stationary; the persistent ACF confirms slow mixing).
3. Multimodal not crossed (or step too small to escape mode вҖ” the rare jumps suggest the chain has trouble moving between modes).
4. Not converged (chains haven't mixed).
5. Step too small (95% acceptance is too high; chain barely moves; ACF drops fast only because it never went anywhere).

### Quiz 5 answers

1. Because the acceptance ratio is a ratio of two posterior densities at different Оё values, and `p(y)` is the same in both вҖ” so it cancels.
2. The Laplace density has a sharp non-differentiable peak at zero, so the MAP can sit exactly at zero. The Normal is smooth at zero, so the MAP is shrunk toward zero but never reaches it.
3. The likelihood factorises: `p(yвҒҪвҒҝвҒәВ№вҒҫ | Оё) = p(yвҒҪвҒҝвҒҫ | Оё) В· p(yвӮҷвӮҠвӮҒ | Оё)`, which requires iid observations.
4. Because MLE divides by `n` and uses an estimated mean (which is itself fitted to minimise residuals); the unbiased estimator divides by `n вҲ’ p вҲ’ 1` (or `n вҲ’ 1`).
5. Their joint distribution is invariant to which rat in the lab gets which index вҖ” order doesn't matter, so they share a common Оёвұј.
6. The ratio of total (between + within) variance to within-chain variance; tends to 1 when chains have converged to the same target.
7. Both prior and data carry information about Оё; the posterior weights them by their respective precisions/sample sizes вҖ” more data вҮ’ more weight on MLE.

